# Doc-tier conventions

Gate 1 and Gate 2 **architecture** acceptance is complete; tier labels and
this lifecycle still apply to **every future edit** under `docs/architecture/`.

Every file under `docs/architecture/` is **Tier A**, **Tier B**, or **Tier C**
and MUST declare its tier in frontmatter. Start from the matching skeleton
under `docs/_templates/`.

## Mandatory frontmatter

```yaml
title:           # string
tier:            # A | B | C
gate:            # 1 | 2 | Rolling  (Tier A = 1; Tier B = 1 or 2; Tier C = Rolling)
owner:           # assignee name (or explicit unassigned marker in draft docs)
peer_reviewer:   # assignee name (SHOULD differ from owner; solo maintainer may self-review)
status:          # Proposed | Accepted | Deferred | Superseded-by
last_review:     # YYYY-MM-DD
adrs:            # [ADR-NNNN, ...]
invariants:      # [INV-AREA-NAME, ...]
```

## Tier semantics

- **Tier A — Gate 1.** Foundations: `README`, `glossary`, `principles`,
  `overview`, `invariants`, `threat-model`. Other docs cite these.
- **Tier B — Gate 1 or Gate 2.** Subsystems/domains. Gate 1 core set is named
  in the architecture plan's `exit-criteria` todo.
- **Tier C — Rolling.** Closes alongside the implementation phase that uses it.
  A status flip to `Accepted` requires all acceptance criteria in the doc's
  "Acceptance criteria for Rolling close" section to be checked.

## Status lifecycle

`Proposed` → (peer-reviewer sign-off + Change Log entry) → `Accepted`.
`Superseded-by:` references another doc or ADR that replaces this one.
No unassigned placeholder markers in an `Accepted` doc narrative (Change Log
excepted). See `docs/architecture/DOC_STANDARDS.md`.

## Change Log

Every status flip writes a Change Log entry naming the reviewer. See
`docs/_governance/REVIEWERS.md` for the exact format.
